I mean on obsedian there is a smart plugin"},{"role":"assistant","content":"Ah, I understand now! You are using an AI plugin (like Smart Connections, Text Generator, BMO Chatbot, or Copilot) inside Obsidian. That changes things a bit!\n\nIn that case, let me explain exactly how my \"powers\" work when connected to your Obsidian vault.\n\nThink of it this way: **I am the brain, and the plugin is the eyes and hands.** I still don't have direct access to your computer's hard drive, but I interact with your files through the plugin. \n\nHere is what I can and cannot do regarding accessing and modifying your Obsidian folders:\n\n### 1. Can I access your folders and notes?\n**Yes, but only how the plugin allows me to.**\nDepending on the plugin you are using, the plugin reads your markdown files and creates an index of them. When you ask a question, the plugin searches your vault, finds the most relevant notes, and sends that text to me (the AI). \n* I **can** read your active note to help clarify, summarize, or continue writing it.\n* I **can** cross-reference multiple notes if the plugin feeds them to me to help you find connections between your ideas.\n* I **cannot** browse your computer outside of the Obsidian vault.\n\n### 2. Can I modify your folders and files?\n**No, I cannot automatically or secretly edit your files.** \nI can only generate text and send it back to the plugin. What happens next is up to the plugin and you:\n* Usually, I output text into a sidebar chat window.\n* You often have to click an **\"Insert\"** or **\"Replace\"** button for my text to actually modify your active note.\n* Even if you use a command like \"Generate text here,\" I am just handing the text to the plugin, which pastes it into your document. I cannot suddenly decide to delete your folder or rewrite a note you aren't working on.\n\n### My \"Powers\" in Obsidian\nWhen integrated into Obsidian, people usually use me for things like this:\n* **Chatting with your vault:** You can ask, \"What did I write about project X last month?\" and I can synthesize an answer based on your notes.\n* **Overcoming writer's block:** You can give me a few bullet points, and I can write them out into full paragraphs.\n* **Formatting:** I can take messy thoughts and organize them into clean markdown tables, lists, or headers.\n* **Metadata & Tagging:** I can read a note and suggest relevant tags or YAML properties/frontmatter to help organize your vault.\n* **Summarizing:** I can take a massive note or a transcribed meeting and give you a 3-bullet-point summary at the top.\n\nWhich Obsidian AI plugin are you currently using? (smart connections, text generator, etc.) If you let me know, I can tell you exactly what features you have access to right now!"},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"could you create a file called stablecoin. And in the file could you separate it into what its stablecoin, is for in AI, How does it work ? Use your own engine and search for the detailed summaries and post them in there."}]}]},"responses":[{"timestamp":1774756789780,"id":"gemini-1774756779124","object":"chat.completion","created":1774756789780,"model":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview","choices":[{"index":0,"message":{"role":"assistant","content":"Because of how plugins work, **I cannot magically create a new file named `stablecoin` in your folder by myself.** You will need to create a new note in Obsidian, name it `stablecoin`, and then either click your plugin's \"Insert\" button or copy and paste the text below. \n\nHowever, I have used my engine to research and compile exactly what you asked for! \n\nHere is the detailed, fully-formatted Markdown content ready for your Obsidian note. Just copy everything inside the box below:\n\n***\n\n```markdown\n# Stablecoins\n\n## What is a Stablecoin?\nA stablecoin is a type of cryptocurrency designed to maintain a stable value by pegging its price to another asset—most commonly a fiat currency like the US Dollar (USD), but sometimes to commodities like gold. \n\nHistorically, cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum are highly volatile, meaning their prices can swing wildly in a single day. Stablecoins were created to offer the best of both worlds: the instant processing, security, and borderless nature of cryptocurrencies, combined with the stable, predictable value of traditional money. Popular examples include **USDC** (USD Coin), **USDT** (Tether), and **DAI**.\n\n## What is it for in AI? (The AI & Crypto Intersection)\nThe intersection of Artificial Intelligence and stablecoins is currently one of the most rapidly developing areas in tech. Stablecoins serve as the **native currency for AI agents**. Because AI programs cannot walk into a bank, provide a passport, and open a typical checking account or get a credit card, they need a digital-native way to transact. \n\nHere is what stablecoins allow AI to do:\n* **Autonomous Micro-transactions:** AI agents can use stablecoins to pay for digital resources in fractions of a cent. For example, your personal AI assistant might pay another AI to scrape a website, paying 0.001 USDC for the task instantly.\n* **Paying for Compute and APIs:** AI models constantly need access to data and API endpoints. An AI agent hooked up to a crypto wallet can autonomously pay for its own server space, GPU compute, or API calls on a per-use basis.\n* **Trustless Collaboration:** Because stablecoin transactions are settled on blockchains via smart contracts, AI agents from different companies can transact with each other securely without needing a middleman or legal agreements. The code enforces the payment.\n* **Bypassing Geo-Restrictions:** Developers building AI globally—whether in the US, Argentina, or Nigeria—can securely pay and be paid in dollar-pegged stablecoins without worrying about local banking infrastructure failing them.\n\n## How Does it Work?\nStablecoins rely on blockchain technology and maintain their \"peg\" (their $1.00 value) through three main mechanisms, depending on the type of stablecoin:\n\n### 1. Fiat-Collateralized (The most common)\n* **Mechanics:** For every single stablecoin minted and issued on the blockchain, there is one real US dollar sitting in a traditional bank account or held in safe assets like short-term US Treasury bonds.\n* **How it works:** If you give the issuing company (like Circle, which makes USDC) $100, they lock that $100 in a bank and generate 100 USDC tokens on the blockchain. When you want your money back, you \"redeem\" the tokens; they destroy the tokens and wire you the $100. Regular audits are conducted to prove the reserve money exists.\n\n### 2. Crypto-Collateralized\n* **Mechanics:** These are backed by other cryptocurrencies, not traditional cash. Because crypto is volatile, these are \"over-collateralized.\" \n* **How it works:** To mint $100 worth of a stablecoin like DAI, a user might have to lock up $150 worth of Ethereum in a smart contract. If the price of Ethereum crashes, the smart contract automatically sells the Ethereum to ensure the stablecoin remains backed by at least $100.\n\n### 3. Algorithmic (Less common today)\n* **Mechanics:** These use complex code and mathematical algorithms to manage supply and demand without actually holding 1-to-1 cash reserves. \n* **How it works:** If the price goes above $1.00, the algorithm creates more coins to increase supply and lower the price. If the price drops below $1.00, the algorithm buys up coins to reduce supply and push the price back up. (Note: These are considered highly risky following the collapse of the Terra/UST algorithmic stablecoin in 2022).\n\n**The Underlying Tech:**\nRegardless of the type, all stablecoins operate as tokens on existing base-layer blockchains (like Ethereum, Solana, or Polygon) and use **Smart Contracts**—self-executing code that automatically processes the transactions, records the ledger, and ensures the rules of the token are followed without a centralized middleman.\n```\n\n***\n\n**How to use this in Obsidian:**\n1. Hit `Ctrl+N` (or `Cmd+N` on Mac) in Obsidian to create a new note.\n2. Title the note `stablecoin`.\n3. Copy the text from the block above and paste it in. \n4. Because it is formatted in **Markdown** (using `#` for headers and `*` for bullets), Obsidian will automatically format it beautifully for you!"},"finish_reason":"stop"}],"usage":{"prompt_tokens":1109,"completion_tokens":1141,"total_tokens":3249}}],"chat_model":{"model_key":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview","chat_completion_model_key":"google#1774722505164"},"error":null},"key":"seq-2026-03-29-02-33-30-1774754471057","stream":true,"chat_thread_key":"seq-2026-03-29-02-33-30","class_name":"SmartCompletion","context_key":"1774754471073","user_message":"could you create a file called stablecoin. And in the file could you separate it into what its stablecoin, is for in AI, How does it work ? Use your own engine and search for the detailed summaries and post them in there.","new_user_message":true},
