both worlds: the instant processing, security, and borderless nature of cryptocurrencies, combined with the stable, predictable value of traditional money. Popular examples include **USDC** (USD Coin), **USDT** (Tether), and **DAI**.\n\n## What is it for in AI? (The AI & Crypto Intersection)\nThe intersection of Artificial Intelligence and stablecoins is currently one of the most rapidly developing areas in tech. Stablecoins serve as the **native currency for AI agents**. Because AI programs cannot walk into a bank, provide a passport, and open a typical checking account or get a credit card, they need a digital-native way to transact. \n\nHere is what stablecoins allow AI to do:\n* **Autonomous Micro-transactions:** AI agents can use stablecoins to pay for digital resources in fractions of a cent. For example, your personal AI assistant might pay another AI to scrape a website, paying 0.001 USDC for the task instantly.\n* **Paying for Compute and APIs:** AI models constantly need access to data and API endpoints. An AI agent hooked up to a crypto wallet can autonomously pay for its own server space, GPU compute, or API calls on a per-use basis.\n* **Trustless Collaboration:** Because stablecoin transactions are settled on blockchains via smart contracts, AI agents from different companies can transact with each other securely without needing a middleman or legal agreements. The code enforces the payment.\n* **Bypassing Geo-Restrictions:** Developers building AI globally—whether in the US, Argentina, or Nigeria—can securely pay and be paid in dollar-pegged stablecoins without worrying about local banking infrastructure failing them.\n\n## How Does it Work?\nStablecoins rely on blockchain technology and maintain their \"peg\" (their $1.00 value) through three main mechanisms, depending on the type of stablecoin:\n\n### 1. Fiat-Collateralized (The most common)\n* **Mechanics:** For every single stablecoin minted and issued on the blockchain, there is one real US dollar sitting in a traditional bank account or held in safe assets like short-term US Treasury bonds.\n* **How it works:** If you give the issuing company (like Circle, which makes USDC) $100, they lock that $100 in a bank and generate 100 USDC tokens on the blockchain. When you want your money back, you \"redeem\" the tokens; they destroy the tokens and wire you the $100. Regular audits are conducted to prove the reserve money exists.\n\n### 2. Crypto-Collateralized\n* **Mechanics:** These are backed by other cryptocurrencies, not traditional cash. Because crypto is volatile, these are \"over-collateralized.\" \n* **How it works:** To mint $100 worth of a stablecoin like DAI, a user might have to lock up $150 worth of Ethereum in a smart contract. If the price of Ethereum crashes, the smart contract automatically sells the Ethereum to ensure the stablecoin remains backed by at least $100.\n\n### 3. Algorithmic (Less common today)\n* **Mechanics:** These use complex code and mathematical algorithms to manage supply and demand without actually holding 1-to-1 cash reserves. \n* **How it works:** If the price goes above $1.00, the algorithm creates more coins to increase supply and lower the price. If the price drops below $1.00, the algorithm buys up coins to reduce supply and push the price back up. (Note: These are considered highly risky following the collapse of the Terra/UST algorithmic stablecoin in 2022).\n\n**The Underlying Tech:**\nRegardless of the type, all stablecoins operate as tokens on existing base-layer blockchains (like Ethereum, Solana, or Polygon) and use **Smart Contracts**—self-executing code that automatically processes the transactions, records the ledger, and ensures the rules of the token are followed without a centralized middleman.\n```\n\n***\n\n**How to use this in Obsidian:**\n1. Hit `Ctrl+N` (or `Cmd+N` on Mac) in Obsidian to create a new note.\n2. Title the note `stablecoin`.\n3. Copy the text from the block above and paste it in. \n4. Because it is formatted in **Markdown** (using `#` for headers and `*` for bullets), Obsidian will automatically format it beautifully for you!"},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"no but I want you to create a file with subfiles is this possible without me handling it ?"}]}]},"responses":[{"timestamp":1774770124187,"id":"gemini-1774770117136","object":"chat.completion","created":1774770124187,"model":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview","choices":[{"index":0,"message":{"role":"assistant","content":"The short answer is: **No, I cannot automatically create files and subfiles for you completely hands-off.** \n\nEven through a smart plugin, you will still have to click a button to execute the action. Here is why, and how you can get as close to your goal as possible.\n\n### Why I can't do it completely automatically:\n1. **Security:** Obsidian plugins are designed to protect your computer. If an AI had the power to silently create, move, or delete files and folders without your permission, it would be a massive security risk (it could accidentally overwrite your important notes or flood your hard drive with thousands of files).\n2. **One-Way Communication:** When you type a prompt, your plugin sends the text to my servers. I generate an answer and send text back. **I do not have a \"save file\" or \"create folder\" button on my end.** That power belongs exclusively to the plugin installed on your computer.\n\n### How to get the closest to \"Automatic\" in Obsidian\n\nWhile I can't create the files automatically, the \"Obsidian way\" to do this is using **Wiki-links**. By putting brackets around words, you tell Obsidian to instantly create sub-files.\n\nIf you copy and paste the block below into your vault, Obsidian will see the bracketed words (like `[[What is a Stablecoin]]`) and turn them into clickable links. When you click them, **Obsidian will automatically create those subfiles for you.**\n\nHere is the master \"Folder\" note you can use:\n\n```markdown\n# Stablecoin Master File\n\nWelcome to the Stablecoin directory. Click on any of the subfiles below to open or create the document.\n\n### Subfiles:\n1. [[What is a Stablecoin]] - Definitions and real-world examples (USDC, Tether).\n2. [[Stablecoins in AI]] - How AI agents use crypto for microtransactions and API payments.\n3. [[How Stablecoins Work]] - Fiat-backed, Crypto-backed, and Algorithmic mechanisms.\n\n***\n*Note: To generate the content inside these subfiles, click the link to open the new empty note, and ask your AI plugin: \"Write a summary for this note's title.\"*\n```\n\n### Are there plugins that CAN do what you are asking?\nIf you truly want an AI that can build folder structures and populate multiple files at once without you doing it manually, standard chat plugins (like Smart Connections) won't do it. \n\nYou would need to look into **Agentic Workflows** or advanced scripting tools inside Obsidian:\n1. **Text Generator Plugin (Auto-Agents):** This plugin allows you to run complex scripts where an AI is given \"tools\" to create files.\n2. **Templater + AI:** You can write a Javascript script inside the \"Templater\" plugin that asks me for a JSON file, and then the script uses my answer to automatically generate folders and `.md` files on your hard drive.\n3. **Local AI Agents (like AutoGPT or OpenInterpreter):** These are separate programs you run on your computer (outside of Obsidian) that you actually give permission to control your mouse, keyboard, and file explorer.\n\nWould you like me to write out the detailed text for those 3 subfiles so you can easily paste them in once you click the links?"},"finish_reason":"stop"}],"usage":{"prompt_tokens":2272,"completion_tokens":706,"total_tokens":4032}}],"chat_model":{"model_key":"gemini-3.1-pro-preview","chat_completion_model_key":"google#1774722505164"},"error":null},"key":"seq-2026-03-29-02-33-30-1774769780226","stream":true,"chat_thread_key":"seq-2026-03-29-02-33-30","class_name":"SmartCompletion","context_key":"1774769780239","user_message":"no but I want you to create a file with subfiles is this possible without me handling it ?","new_user_message":true},